Purpose of This Document

I am the tenant, and I have prepared this document myself to assist whoever is looking at this tenancy in Victoria – for example VCAT, Consumer Affairs Victoria, the Business Licensing Authority, the RTBA, or any other regulator or decision-maker. My goal is to present a clear summary of what happened, connect the events to my rights as a renter, and explain the impacts shown by the evidence. All information is based on the evidence already filed (in the BUNDLE and other attachments).

This timeline should be read together with my Applicant’s Schedule of Parties (separate document). That schedule lists every person and company involved in this tenancy, their official roles (including how they are recorded on the Consumer Affairs Victoria register), and how they connect to the events described here. Where I use names like “Sylvia Hao”, “Johnson Tan”, “Shaun Young” or “Jamie Ong” in this document, they match the entries in that Schedule.

In this document I sometimes use the word “tribunal” for simplicity. When I do, I mean any Victorian decision-maker or oversight body reviewing this matter, unless I am clearly talking about a specific VCAT case number or order.

Executive Summary

This is a summary of my dispute with my rental agent, Areal Property. My co-tenant is Podjana Tienmon.

  • Unrepaired Damage: I first reported a water leak that was causing the walls and ceiling in my master bedroom to bulge on April 16, 2025. While the pipe was fixed on May 2, the damage to the room (walls, carpet, dampness) was not. For over 224 days, I could not use my master bedroom and had to sleep in the living room. As of November 26, 2025, there is no proof that the repairs were ever finished.
  • Charged Full Rent for Unusable Room: Even though my master bedroom was unusable, the agent continued to charge me full rent. This includes invoice #010956 for $2,825 (for Nov 23–Dec 22, 2025) and a payment reminder email sent on November 20, 2025.
  • Eviction Notice After My Complaint: Just 17 days after I lodged my RDRV case on June 24, 2025—and only 14 days after RDRV recorded that case as withdrawn on June 27—the agent gave me a Notice to Vacate. I believe this was in direct response to me exercising my rights.
  • Improper Eviction Notice: The eviction notice relied on a contractor report arranged by the agent and an internal “Message Thread Franklin St” email trail. I have never been shown any report or order from a council, building surveyor, or other public authority declaring the premises unsafe, even though the notice form itself warns that VCAT may find a notice invalid if it is not accompanied by the required documentary evidence.
  • VCAT's Previous Decision: I went to VCAT to challenge the eviction notice. The agent also applied to have me removed. On August 15, 2025, the tribunal dismissed the agent's application, and I was not evicted.
  • Agent's Internal Failures: The agent's own documents list mould and dampness as "urgent repairs." However, they did not follow their own procedure in my case. The agent also claims I "refused access," but my emails and messages show I was willing to grant access as long as it was safe and I was given a temporary place to stay during the disruptive work.

Ongoing Impact: As of Nov 26, 2025, this dispute has lasted for over 224 days. It has caused constant disruption and stress, and has put my studies and my student visa at risk.

My Story of What Happened

Start of lease period:
My lease agreement for Unit 1803, 243 Franklin St was signed on Oct 16, 2024, with my co-tenant Podjana Tienmon, and the tenancy commenced on Dec 23, 2024. Before the problems began, I always paid my rent in full and on time (receipts #85835, #87045). In February 2025, Areal Property took over as the agent and sent me an after-hours emergency trades list, so I know they had a system for urgent repairs from the very beginning.

Tenant’s Compliance & Agency’s Duty:
From the beginning of the tenancy, I strictly adhered to my obligations and consistently paid rent on time, as shown by the monthly receipts from February through October 2025 (E005, p.44; E008, p.48; E020, p.81; E034, p.118; E074, p.228; E157, p.383; E173, p.464; E195, p.510; E201, p.518). The Agency itself confirmed it had resources for urgent repairs when it provided the “Emergency Maintenance Trades Contact List” on 7 Feb 2025 (E003, p.40–41) and undertook this duty under the Residential Rental Agreement (E001, p.17), yet later failed to use those resources when my bedroom was damaged.

The Water Leak incident begins – Apr 16, 2025:
In mid-April, the walls and ceiling of my master bedroom started to swell from a water leak. I reported it immediately via email with photos. At that time, Sylvia Hao was the property manager. Even though it was the Easter holiday, I sent follow-up emails because the mould and musty smell were getting worse. Despite the problems, I continued to pay my full rent (receipt #88184).

Failure to Act on Urgent Report:
I sent an urgent report with photos showing the wall swelling and damage (E015, p.71–74), but received only an automated reply (E016, p.75) instead of an emergency response. I escalated again on 23 April when mould and ceiling damage appeared (E019, p.83–89), yet the Agency treated it as routine and merely scheduled a standard inspection (E022, p.93) instead of dispatching emergency repairs.

The leak is fixed, but the room is still damaged:
In early May, a tradesperson repaired the hot water pipe that caused the leak. However, the walls and carpet were still swollen, stained, and smelled musty.
I emailed Sylvia asking for a timeline to fix the rest of the damage. She just said she was “waiting for a report” and gave no timeline or offered any help. I sent more photos of the damaged walls, but she didn't seem to respond to them.

Incomplete Rectification & Misleading Conduct:
Although the leak source was repaired on 2 May 2025 (E027, p.100), the Agency did nothing to make my bedroom habitable. I informed them on 9–10 May that the walls remained warped, stained and damaged (E028, p.101; E030, p.103–105). Their internal records labelled it a “Water Leak Lot” issue (E032, p.110–117), yet they left me living in the damaged room for weeks and I had to keep chasing them for updates (E031, p.106).

June 2025 – I send a formal complaint and file with RDRV:
On June 6, 2025, I sent a formal letter explaining how the damaged bedroom was affecting my sleep and studies. Sylvia's response was to suggest I find my own temporary accommodation, or accept an offer in a distant suburb (Mount Waverley). An offer of accommodation 1.5 hours away from my university was not a real solution, as it would have directly threatened my ability to meet my student visa attendance requirements.
I felt these unreasonable offers just shifted the entire cost and burden onto me, so I filed a case with RDRV (RT252398) on June 24 to formally ask for repairs and compensation. RDRV later recorded that case as withdrawn on June 27, 2025, even though the damage and lack of accommodation were still unresolved, which is why I then had to take the matter to VCAT.

Formal Demand for Resolution:
After weeks of inaction, I issued a Formal Demand Letter and Tenant Statement (E046, p.146–147; E047, p.152–153) describing the impact on my living conditions. The Agency offered a vague $800 “compensation” (E048, p.155; E054, p.177) with no calculation. When I asked for clarification and a proper plan (E050, p.162–165), they still gave no transparent answers. Instead, they began asserting I was “refusing access,” despite my written statements confirming I would grant access once a safe, clear plan was provided (E045, p.144; E053, p.172).

Late June–Early July 2025 – Johnson Tan takes over:
After I filed with RDRV, Johnson Tan started emailing me about access for repairs. His emails suggested that if a tradesperson couldn't get access, I might be charged a fee or have it taken from my bond, but he was not clear about the costs.
I asked for six basic pieces of information about the tradesperson (their company, license, scope of work, etc.) so I could be sure, but the information he gave me was incomplete. This prevented me from giving my fully informed consent for them to enter my home.

July 11, 2025 – I receive an eviction notice:
Just 17 days after I filed my case with RDRV—and only 14 days after RDRV recorded it as withdrawn—the agent issued a Notice to Vacate for "unsafe premises," telling me I had to leave within 3 days. This felt completely unfair, as the main problem was my damaged bedroom and the agent's failure to offer proper accommodation for the repairs.
I had no choice but to appeal the notice to VCAT (R202518214_00). The agent then filed their own case to have me evicted (R202518589_00).

Retaliatory Eviction & Withheld Evidence:
The Notice to Vacate on 11 July 2025 relied on an internal “Message Thread” as “documentary evidence” (E118, p.323; E123, p.324; E121, p.317–320). That thread shows the Owners Corporation suggested temporary accommodation, yet the Agency never offered it; instead, they used the repair works as a pretext to evict me within three days. I immediately challenged this by filing a VCAT application (E129, p.349) to contest what I believe was an unjust eviction.

August 2025 – VCAT dismisses the agent's case:
In August, another manager, Shaun Young, submitted documents for the agent's case against me, repeating the claims that I "refused access." On August 15, 2025, VCAT dismissed the agent's application to evict me. I remained in the apartment, and my bedroom was still not fixed.
Later that month, I tried to end the dispute by offering to settle for $10,000, but Jamie Ong (Head of Property Management) rejected it completely. He continued to blame the Owners Corporation and insisted the problem was about "access," not about their failure to provide temporary accommodation or a rent reduction.

September–November 2025 – The problems continue:
In September, I received more entry notices for major repair work, but still with no clear offer of a place to stay or a reduction in rent.
Emails from September–November 2025, mostly from Johnson Tan, focused on rent reminders and sending monthly emergency trades lists rather than discussing the repair plan. Meanwhile, I received warning letters from my college (Sacred Heart International College) about my attendance, which put my student visa at risk (as per documents attached in the supporting evidence section).
On Nov 19, 2025, the agent issued another invoice (#010956) for full rent of $2,825, followed by a reminder email to pay on time.

Continued Harassment & Academic Impact:
Even while the dispute was before VCAT, the Agency escalated pressure by issuing formal Warning Letters on 1 September (E176, p.470) and 15 September (E189, p.505). They also sent a stream of Notices of Entry (E170, p.456; E187, p.493) without genuine coordination, disrupting my quiet enjoyment. This stress harmed my studies, forcing me to seek a school reassessment (E197, p.514–515) and medical attention (E063, p.195). Despite calling the unit “unsafe” in July, they kept issuing full rent invoices in October (E198, p.516; E199, p.517), showing their priority was collecting money rather than tenant safety.

Summary of the situation:
For over 224 days (from April 16 to November 26, 2025), I could not use my master bedroom due to the water damage. I continued to pay my full rent the entire time.
Meanwhile, I had to live with the moisture and smell, constant disruptions, and the stress of dealing with legal cases, all of which put my education and visa in jeopardy.
The rest of this document provides detailed monthly tables and evidence to show exactly what happened.

Summary of the Agent's Main Failures

What Went Wrong My Rights That Were Affected Key Evidence
Failure to do repairs My right to a safe and repaired home (RTA s 68) Damage was left for 224+ days (Apr 16 – Nov 26, 2025); photos show mould, bulging walls, and a damaged carpet.
Disturbance to my quiet enjoyment My right to live peacefully in my home (RTA s 67) Bedroom was unusable, forcing me to sleep in the living room; the musty smell affected the entire apartment, and constant entry notices caused stress.
Charging full rent for a damaged home My right to reduced rent for loss of amenity (RTA s 67) The agent charged full rent ($2,825) for Nov-Dec 2025 (Invoice #010956) and never offered a proper rent reduction.
Eviction notice seemed retaliatory My right to complain without being punished under the Residential Tenancies Act The agent issued an eviction notice on Jul 11, 2025, just 17 days after I formally sought help from RDRV (and 14 days after RDRV recorded the case as withdrawn), suggesting the notice was for retaliation, not safety. VCAT later dismissed the agent's case.
Improper eviction notice My right to a valid notice under the Residential Tenancies Act The notice claimed the unit was "unsafe" but relied only on the contractor’s report and an internal Message Thread; I was never shown any report or order from a council, building surveyor or public authority declaring the premises unsafe, even though the notice form itself says VCAT may find a notice invalid without the required documentary evidence.
False claims against me My right to fair and honest treatment under the Australian Consumer Law The agent claimed I "refused access" to try and charge me $711.70, but my emails show I agreed to access under reasonable and safe conditions, which is my legal right.
Using legal processes to pressure me My right to be safe from retaliation under the Residential Tenancies Act The agent filed for possession (R202518589_00) using a disputed notice, and VCAT dismissed their application on Aug 15, 2025.
Constant entry notices My right to privacy and quiet enjoyment (RTA ss 75, 67) I received back-to-back entry notices for Jul and a block for Sep 17-22, causing major disruption.
Ignoring my situation as a student Basic fairness and care Two warning letters from Sacred Heart International College dated 11 and 15 September 2025, plus my special consideration request, all showing that the tenancy problems were putting my attendance and visa at risk.

In February and March 2025, I received the “Welcome to Areal Property” email and the monthly after-hours emergency trades lists. These messages clearly invited me to contact Mr Ong if I had any feedback about the service, and attached the emergency trades contact list for Hawthorn (including Flood Response and licensed plumbers). Later, each of my rent receipts from different staff (Jessica Xie, Hilary Ho, and then Sylvia Hao) repeated the same line: if I had any feedback about their service, I should contact their manager, Jamie Ong (Head of Property Management). This shows he was the escalation point for problems from the very start of my tenancy, not someone “far away” from day-to-day issues.

On 23–24 April 2025, when the water damage in my bedroom had clearly become serious, I sent a second follow-up email to Ms Hao titled “Urgent Water Damage Escalation – Immediate Action Required (Unit 1803)” with photos and a detailed explanation of ceiling stains, wall swelling, wet carpet, musty smell and the risk of mould. That email shows Mr Ong in the copied recipients, and on the same day I received a routine inspection notice from Ms Hao that also copied him and listed “bathroom mould” as something they would look for. Despite this, I never received any direct response from him at that time.

In other words, by late April 2025 Mr Ong had been:

  • Named as the manager to contact in multiple emails and rent receipts.
  • Given a copy of my detailed urgent water-damage escalation email, including photos and a clear description of the health risks.
  • Copied into routine inspection correspondence that talked about checking for mould.

Yet there is no evidence that he intervened to make sure the urgent repairs were handled properly, or that he contacted me directly to check on my situation. The only time I clearly saw his direct involvement was later, after the eviction application had already been dismissed, when he rejected my settlement offer, blamed the Owners Corporation, and warned me about further legal action instead of acknowledging what had happened.

By allowing his name to be used on all the “if you have any feedback, contact my manager” messages, while staying silent when a serious problem was escalated and copied to him, Mr Ong created the impression that there was a functioning complaints path when in reality there was not. When he finally did step in, it was to say no to a reasonable settlement and to continue the agency’s position that the problem was my “refusal of access” rather than their failure to provide safe conditions and proper accommodation during repairs. Even after I asked him to stop Mr Tan from contacting me, Johnson Tan was still allowed to send rent reminders and invoice #010956 for the full rent.

Overall, I see Mr Ong’s conduct as a management failure in three ways:

  • He allowed his name to be used as the complaints contact while not responding when a serious issue reached him.
  • He did not step in to stop threats about bond deductions and fees, or to correct the use of a retaliatory Notice to Vacate.
  • When he finally engaged, it was to defend the agency and threaten more legal action, rather than to fix the problem and support a fair outcome.

5. Officers in Effective Control (OIEC) – Cheng Wee Low and Warren Andrew Tate

As the people legally in charge of the licensed agencies involved, the ultimate responsibility for compliance rests with them.

Systemic and Management Failures

The Failure of a System: From Agent to Executive

This dispute is not about one mistake by one property manager. The evidence points to a complete breakdown of the agency's duties at every level, from the agent on the ground to the highest level of management.

  • The Agency Broke Its Own Rules: My problem (mould/damp) was classified as an "urgent repair" by the agency's own written policy. The failure to act for over 224 days is a failure of the entire system that management is paid to enforce.
  • Management Endorsed Retaliation: After a junior agent issued a retaliatory eviction notice, and after VCAT dismissed that case, the Head of Property Management, Jamie Ong, personally rejected my good-faith settlement offer. This shows the aggressive strategy was approved from the top.
  • The Person in Charge Was Absent: The Officer in Effective Control (OIEC), who holds the ultimate legal responsibility for the agency, was completely absent throughout this entire 224+ day ordeal.
  • Professional advice about safety and accommodation was ignored: Both the OC (Highrise Strata) and the contractor (FIXD) said the bedroom would be unsafe during remediation and asked the agent to guide us on arranging private accommodation for the 7–14 day drying period. Instead of acting on that advice, the agent used the same documents to justify an “unsafe premises” NTV and to claim I had “refused access.”

The email trail also shows how the agency’s system looked good on paper but failed in practice. From February 2025 onwards, I regularly received “after-hours emergency trades list” emails and rent receipts that all told me to contact the Head of Property Management, Jamie Ong, if I had any feedback about the service. When the worst problem actually happened—a serious water leak that damaged my bedroom and created a mould risk—I followed their process, reported it early, called the emergency contractor on their list, and sent a detailed escalation email with photos. That escalation email was copied to Mr Ong, and the same day he was also copied into a routine inspection notice that talked about checking for mould, but there is no evidence that anyone at management level actually stepped in to fix things or to support me.

Instead, the pattern that emerges is:

  • Front-line staff (first Ms Ho, then Ms Hao, then Mr Tan, then Mr Young) each handled part of the problem but passed it on without a proper solution.
  • The senior manager named in every email as the contact for feedback received my escalation but stayed silent while my room remained damaged.
  • When the agency did act strongly, it was not to repair the damage or offer fair accommodation, but to send a Notice to Vacate, file a possession case at the tribunal, and keep charging me full rent.

At the first VCAT hearing on the agent’s possession application, none of the people who had actually made the key decisions – not Ms Hao, not Mr Tan, and not Mr Ong – came to face the tribunal. Instead, the agency sent Mr Shaun Young, who had been brought into the file later and could not clearly explain why the notice had been issued, what evidence supported it, or how their own emails fitted together. I barely needed to speak; it was obvious from his answers that even the person they sent did not fully understand or stand behind what the agency had done.

These key facts show a pattern of negligence that goes far beyond a simple dispute and points to a serious failure of governance at the executive level.

Beyond the actions of individual managers, I believe there are wider problems with how the Areal Property agency operates. The key issues were:

  • Poor and inconsistent communication, which forced me to chase them for updates.
  • Not providing clear and complete information before needing to enter my home.
  • Not offering clear or fair options for things like temporary accommodation, which shifted the burden and cost entirely onto me.

Key Evidence Highlights

  1. The “Unsafe” Hypocrisy: The Agency claimed the premises were “unsafe” on 11 July 2025 to justify eviction (E123, p.324), yet kept demanding and receiving full rent: 25 Jul ($2,825) (E157, p.383), 27 Aug (E173, p.464), 30 Sep (E195, p.510), and Invoice #010956 in Nov (E199, p.517). Either it was safe (and the notice was false) or unsafe (and they collected rent for a dangerous home). The “safety” claim was a tactic, not protection.
  2. Retaliation via Entry Notices: After VCAT dismissed their possession attempt on 15 Aug 2025 (E163, p.440), they flooded me with block entry notices for 17–22 Sep (E187, p.493) instead of coordinating a fair repair plan. As a student, being told to surrender my bedroom every day for a week with no alternate place to sleep was pressure, not remediation.
  3. Academic Harm You Can Count: The housing chaos damaged my studies and visa stability: warning letters on 1 Sep (E176, p.470) and 15 Sep (E189, p.505), plus a $300 school reassessment cost (E197, p.514–515). This is measurable harm to my education and future.
  4. The Truth About Access: They told VCAT I “refused access,” yet my SMS to the tradesperson on 17 Sep 2025 (E193, p.509) says: “I am not refusing access… you may attend today.” My only question for five months was: “Where do I sleep while you work?” They blamed me to hide their lack of planning.
  5. The Manager Merry-Go-Round: Four managers cycled through instead of solving the problem—Hilary Ho in April (E013), Sylvia Hao in May (E030), Johnson Tan in June (E067), and Shaun Young signing possession papers in August (E162). Passing the file around turned a simple leak into a six-month legal battle.
  6. Ignored Safety Before the Leak: On 2 April 2025 I reported a broken bed frame with exposed nails (E010, p.52)—easy to fix, but ignored. If they would not fix a simple bed hazard, it is no surprise they left me sleeping in a mouldy bedroom for months.

Final Summary

Looking back at all the events, it is clear to me that no one at Areal Property—from the property managers to the Officer in Effective Control—has ever taken responsibility for the damage to my home and the impact on my life over these 224+ days.

Instead, the agency focused on collecting full rent from me every month. The constant rent reminders and invoices, while my home was damaged and my health and studies were at risk, showed me that they cared more about money than my safety and wellbeing.

Even when I tried to be reasonable and made a good-faith settlement offer, the Head of Property Management, Jamie Ong, rejected it completely. There has been no sign that the conduct of the managers who caused so much stress has been reviewed, or that anything will be done to prevent them from doing this to someone else. It shows a serious lack of leadership at the very top.

Even at the VCAT hearing, none of the people who had been dealing with me from the start—like Sylvia Hao or Johnson Tan—showed up. The agency sent only Shaun Young, who joined later and was not there when the damage first happened, to answer the Tribunal’s questions. From what I saw, he could not clearly explain the documents the agency filed. As an international student, I had to walk the Tribunal through the events and point to each document myself so they could understand what really happened in my home.

This document is my honest, factual summary of what happened, backed up by the evidence I have submitted. The actions of the agency and its staff caused real harm—to my health, my quality of life, my education, and my visa status. My VCAT applications set out the formal remedies I sought there; other decision-makers can use this record to understand the conduct and its impact.
